Do Democracies Redistribute More to the Poor than Autocracies?
Shouyang Wang
In this report, we examine whether democracies redistribute more to the poor and the consequences of
missing data. A long-standing debate in the social sciences is whether democracies redistribute more
to the poor than autocracies. Research on this topic is challenging, however, due to the prevalence
of missing data. Information about particular countries (and variables) are often missing, and this
absence of data is not random. For example, autocratic countries are less likely to report their data
to international institutions like the World Bank. Also, starting in the 1990s, countries have become
better at both collecting and reporting data on dierent indicators such as economic growth or infant
mortality. So if we just analyze data without taking these factors into account, we might bias our results.
This exercise is based on the following prominent paper:Ross, Michael (2006), Is Democracy Good for
the Poor,American Journal of Political Science, Vol. 50,No. 4, pp. 860 - 874.Prior to Ross' work, the
prevailing belief was that democracies redistributed to the poor more than autocracies. Ross' work
challenged this belief. Specically, Ross argued that previous studies had paid insucient attention to
dierences between countries and time trends. Further, Ross argued that their analysis did not address
the problem of missing data.

Interpretation:
Our primary goal is to map the relationship between polity score and infant mortality by evaluating if
β
polity
is non-zero. At population level, we can never know the true slope of
β
polity
. However, we can
calculate the sample slope and make inferences about the population.
∴
the null hypothesis
H
0
regarding the polity score is that the gradient is 0 or there is no relationship
between polity score and infant mortality. The alternative hypothesis
H
a
is the mathematical opposite
of
H
0
, such that we can either observe a positive or negative relationship.
We then see if there is enough evidence to reject
H
0
. Table 2 shows the analysis result. We focus
primarily on
polity
and we will interpret all 4 columns: estimate, std.error, statistics, and p.value.
estimate: the column is used to predict the value of the response variable. In this case, we can conclude
that, while holding all other predictor variables constant, the change in infant mortality associated with
an increase of polity score of 1 is -1.71% based on the equation we obtained previously.
std.error: the average amount that the estimate deviates from the actual value. This number is often
used to calculate the condence interval. We see that a std.error is 0.0017 which is relative low to the
coecient, indicating that our model is decent based on the input data.
statistics: this is the equivalent of the t-value, which is calculated using estimate / std.error. If the
t-value is relatively high, the coecient is statistically signicant.
p.value: this is the p value for the t test. The smaller the P-value, the stronger the statistical signicance.
In other words, it is very likely that the relationship between the dependent variable and independent
variable is due to random chance. Hence, if P is suciently small (<0.05), we can reject the null
hypothesis that there is no relationship between polity score and infant mortality.
Based on all 4 statistics above, we can reject the null hypothesis and conclude that democratic countries
tend to have a lower infant mortality rate(deaths per 1000 children under 5).
#add fixed effects by country and year
mod2 <- lm(df, formula = log(inf_mort) ~ polity
+ gdp_growth + log(gdp_per_capita) + log(pop_density) +
factor(year) + factor(country_name))
Instead of showing everything(there are too many predictors), we will only show the predictors that are
statistically insignicant.
#find all predictors with a p value > 0.05
summary_mod2 <- tidy(summary(mod2)) %>%
mutate(note = ifelse(p.value > 0.05, 'not_sig', 'sig')) %>%
filter(note == "not_sig")
kable(summary_mod2)

As we can see here, for the ltered country that are not statistically signicant, their political scores
are lower on average. Those ltered countries tend to be on the autocratic side of the spectrum.
Summary: After adding xed eects by country and year, we see that polity score is not a statistically
signicant term (p = 0.12, relatively small t value (compared to other terms) of -1.57) that correlates
to infant mortality, a measurement of democracy redistribution. The nding contradicts the previous
ndings that democratic countries tend to have a lower infant mortality rate. We see that factors that
are specic to each country play an important role when predicting the infant mortality rate.
We can also see that the year that the data was recorded plays a signicant role in the analysis.
The year and the proportion of missing data are strongly correlated. As we discovered previously 
the percentage of missing data has signicantly decreased over time (we can also observe that the
t-value of years increases over time)since the 1970s. Hence, missing data has a signicant impact when
calculating the outcome variable infant mortality.
